We can use the Taylor expansion of `f(y)` around `x`:
`f(y) = f(x) + ∇f(x)·(y-x) + (1/2)·(y-x)·Hf(x)·(y-x) + R`
where `R` is the remainder term.

Then, `f(x) - f(y) = -∇f(x)·(y-x) - (1/2)·(y-x)·Hf(x)·(y-x) - R`.

Taking the absolute value, we get:
`|f(x) - f(y)| = | -∇f(x)·(y-x) - (1/2)·(y-x)·Hf(x)·(y-x) - R |`

We can bound this using the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality and the fact that the mixed partial derivatives are bounded.

